# Essential fatty acids and attention-deficit–hyperactivity disorder: a systematic review
**Autores**: Not specified
**Año**: 2009
**Journal**: Scientific Paper
**DOI/Link**: N/A

## Abstract
Not found

## Key Findings
discussion in many countries.
These fatty acids have been used as both a primary and an
adjunctive treatment for ADHD. Therefore, the scientiﬁc
evaluation of these supplements is highly important. Sev-
eral review articles and reports have been published in this
ﬁeld, and the reader is encouraged to consult these in
detail.1–4 The purpose of the current review is to provide
an updated, systematic overview of the theory and use of
EFAs in ADHD.
Humans are unable to synthesize linoleic acid, an
omega-6 fatty acid, and a-linolenic acid (ALA), an omega-
3 fatty acid, de novo. The main dietary sources of linoleic
acid are vegetable oils (such as corn, sunﬂower and cotton)
and their seeds. ALA is found in vegetable oils (especially
in soy, canola, ﬂaxseed, and walnut oils), ﬂaxseeds, and wal-
nuts.5
